{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Workflow-engine remediation: unify LLM functionality on the engine, restore visual editing, document intended use\n\n## Context\n\nGaps surfaced while finalizing the plan-review gate (epic `5fd2`). This epic CAPTURES scope + initial\nconcerns; a dedicated brainstorm session does the deep design BEFORE implementation (per `joe-brainstorm`).\n\n1. **No usage documentation.** The workflow engine (epic `a88f`, closed) has no project doc describing its\n   INTENDED USE — when to author a workflow vs. a bespoke operation, the YAML DSL, the human review/edit\n   pattern, the prompt-library + eval seam. Knowledge is scattered across `README` (packaging),\n   `docs/llm-framework.md` (agent-step angle), `CLAUDE.md` (MCP tools), and the `a88f` tickets. There is no\n   `docs/workflow-engine.md`.\n2. **LLM functionality is fragmented across two patterns.** `review_ticket`/`review_code`/`scan_spec` were\n   reframed as workflows (WS-K2), but `verify_completion` (completion-verifier) was NOT, and the plan-review\n   gate (`5fd2`) is currently specced as a bespoke orchestrator \"mirroring verify_completion.\" LLM review\n   logic therefore lives in BOTH the engine AND bespoke operations — the engine should be the single substrate.\n3. **A core requirement was deferred.** BIDIRECTIONAL visual workflow editing was a core user requirement;\n   `a88f` shipped only a read-only Mermaid render and explicitly deferred a bidirectional editor (story WS-I,\n   \"out of scope\"). That deferral contradicts the expressed intent and must be revisited — but we should\n   almost certainly NOT build a canvas editor ourselves; adopt a workflow FORMAT/technology with an\n   established ecosystem of visual-editing tools.\n4. **The gate's production prompts have no home yet (and the experiments are not it).** The plan-review\n   gate's criteria/prompts currently exist ONLY as TRANSIENT EXPERIMENT artifacts (`criteria_v*.json` under\n   `docs/experiments/`) — useful reference that grounded the design, but explicitly NOT a permanent home and\n   NOT this epic's deliverable. When the gate is implemented (epic `5fd2`), its PRODUCTION prompts must be\n   authored into the engine's git-native prompt library (`resolve_prompt` / prompts-as-files / Langfuse\n   prompt-management + the Inspect/promptfoo eval seam). The error to avoid: treating an experiment artifact\n   as the durable deliverable. (The experiments stay where they are, labeled as experiments — no migration.)\n\n## Scope (workstreams — decomposed AFTER the brainstorm)\n\n- **WS-DOC — usage documentation.** Author `docs/workflow-engine.md`: intended use; when to use a workflow\n  vs. a bespoke op; the YAML DSL + schema; author/validate/render/run; scripted vs. agentic steps; the\n  prompt-library + eval seam; and **the three-tier (three-pass) LLM-review gating pattern** (Pass-1 evidence\n  records → Pass-2 independent binary-verify → Pass-3 deterministic gate; from epic `9da1`). This doc is the\n  canonical anchor the review epics (`5fd2`/`9da1`) point at. It also documents the **agent-vs-single-turn bright line** for authoring new reviewers (see Concerns). It also includes **prompt-authoring guidance for reviewer criteria** — the research-backed do/don't list below — so new criteria use techniques that actually raise reliability.\n- **WS-MIGRATE — one substrate for all LLM functionality.** Migrate `verify_completion` onto the engine\n  (revisiting `9da1`'s explicit out-of-scope hold); build the plan-review gate (`5fd2`) ON the engine, not\n  as a bespoke orchestrator; confirm `review_ticket`/`review_code`/`scan_spec` parity. CAVEAT: the engine is\n  a thin LINEAR executor (graphlib) — the gate's dynamic fan-out (Pass-1 → N findings → N Pass-2 verifier\n  calls) + registry-driven facet-chunking may exceed the DSL; resolve whether the DSL gains map/fan-out\n  steps or the orchestration stays scripted inside steps.\n- **WS-PROMPTS — the gate's PRODUCTION prompts live on the engine (no migration of prototypes).** When\n  the plan-review gate is implemented (`5fd2`), its production criteria/prompts must be authored INTO the\n  engine's prompt-library / `resolve_prompt` / prompts-as-files + eval seam — versioned, evaluable, visually\n  reviewable like other workflow prompts (the eval SEAM here serves the per-criterion eval SUITE that lives in the plan-review epic `5fd2`). The `criteria_v*.json` under `docs/experiments/` are EXPERIMENT\n  REFERENCES (grounding) — NOT the deliverable, NOT to be moved or promoted; they remain in place, labeled as\n  experiments. This WS concerns where the FUTURE production prompts live, not relocating the prototypes.\n- **WS-EVAL-EXISTING — eval coverage for the EXISTING (migrated) reviewer prompts.** As `verify_completion` +\n  `review_ticket` / `review_code` / `scan_spec` migrate onto the engine (WS-MIGRATE) and their prompts move\n  into the prompt library (WS-PROMPTS), give each EXISTING prompt a labeled eval set in the shared eval seam\n  (promptfoo / Inspect) — recall / false-accept / false-fire — drawn from the same three corpuses (DSO\n  read-only + snap-oakhart-manual + rebar's own tickets), so a migration or prompt edit is regression-gated,\n  not a blind cutover (the WS-K2 \"parallel-run-and-diff old vs new\" discipline, made into a standing eval).\n  This is the EXISTING-prompt counterpart to the plan-review epic `5fd2`'s NEW-prompt per-criterion eval\n  suite; both share this epic's eval-seam infrastructure.\n- **WS-CLEANUP — retire the weaker/undeveloped example workflows added to exercise the engine.** The engine\n  shipped demonstrators to prove it out; keep only the ones that earn their keep and remove the rest so the\n  built-in surface is honest. Current inventory: the `code_review` example workflow\n  (`src/rebar/llm/workflow/examples/code_review.yaml`, the end-to-end demonstrator) and the `rebar workflow\n  new` scaffold template (`templates.py`); the reviewers are reframed in code (`review_workflows.py`), not as\n  standalone YAML (no strangler-fig example exists despite the WS-K story title). EXACT removal set is Joe's\n  call (pending his selection); preserve forwarding shims / public API for anything still referenced.\n- **WS-VISUAL — bidirectional visual editing via an established ecosystem.** Decide a workflow\n  format/technology whose ecosystem ALREADY provides visual (ideally bidirectional) editing — rather than\n  building our own canvas. Candidates to weigh in the brainstorm (NOT decided): BPMN (bpmn.io / Camunda\n  Modeler), n8n, Node-RED, Argo Workflows, draw.io/diagrams.net round-trip, a Mermaid-edit round-trip, or a\n  JSON/YAML graph with an off-the-shelf editor. CONSTRAINT: preserve clean git diffs + schema-validated text\n  (the `a88f` invariant).\n- **WS-VALIDATE — capabilities vs alternatives.** Re-evaluate the engine's capabilities against alternatives\n  to confirm we built the right thing: Langflow (rejected in `a88f` — re-confirm), Burr (the `a88f`\n  tripwire), Temporal/Prefect/Dagster, LangGraph-as-engine, n8n/Node-RED, Argo. Output: a kept-or-pivot\n  recommendation.\n- **WS-VISUAL-EVAL (candidate) — visual prompt + eval review.** Today Langfuse (optional, when keys set)\n  gives a prompt-management + trace UI and `[eval]` wires Inspect/promptfoo (their own viewers), but there\n  is no first-class, documented surface for humans to visually review prompts + eval STATUS together. Decide\n  whether to make this first-class (Langfuse / Inspect / promptfoo, or other), and whether `a88f`'s\n  \"Langfuse = trace sink only\" scoping should widen.\n- **WS-INTENT-ALIGN (during this epic — NOT now).** The orchestrator working this epic should LOCATE the\n  session log where the workflow engine was DESIGNED (candidate: the `a88f` implementation log\n  `2eb5-1cdb-daaa-4655`; there may be an earlier design/brainstorm log) and align what was BUILT against the\n  intent the user expressed there — specifically the visual-editing requirement — to ground WS-VISUAL and\n  WS-VALIDATE. This is the manual instance of the intent-source-fidelity check: it presupposes a linked\n  design session log, and the analysis (large-context intent reconstruction) should use a frontier model (Opus).\n\n## Initial thoughts & concerns (to seed the brainstorm)\n\n- **Process failure — a CORE requirement was silently deferred.** Bidirectional visual editing was\n  downgraded to \"out of scope\" in a story without surfacing the conflict with the user's stated intent —\n  the same class of failure as silently descoping the completion-verifier migration.\n- **Review-gate blind spot (carry to `5fd2` / `9da1`).** Our plan-review gates operate on the plan AS\n  WRITTEN. They catch internal contradictions (COH), children-not-covering-the-parent's-ACs (G3), and\n  body-doing-less-than-the-title (E3) — but ONLY when the requirement is recorded in the plan. They CANNOT\n  catch an LLM silently descoping a requirement the USER expressed EXTERNALLY (in conversation/brainstorm)\n  that was never written into the goal/ACs — there is no artifact of the original intent to compare against.\n  Goal↔AC comparison catches it only when a broadly-stated goal visibly conflicts with a carve-out AC\n  (\"migrate ALL reviewers\" vs \"except completion_verifier\"); it does NOT catch the visual-editing case,\n  where the goal ITSELF was already narrowed to \"read-only render.\" The missing capability is an\n  **intent-provenance / requirement-traceability check** comparing the plan against an EXTERNAL intent source.\n  Candidate new plan-review criterion **\"intent-source fidelity\"** with firm constraints: (a) it FIRES ONLY\n  when the ticket is LINKED TO A SESSION LOG (no linked intent source → not-applicable / skip; never\n  fabricate an intent baseline); (b) it runs on a FRONTIER model (e.g. Opus) for the large context and hard\n  intent analysis; (c) it is NOT an agent/tool-using criterion — assessing intent alignment is a text-vs-text\n  comparison of artifacts we already hold (the linked session log + the pre-resolved ticket graph), FED as\n  context to a single call (likely 2-STEP: extract expressed requirements → check the plan-graph against\n  each, like E1/E3/E6). No filesystem/tool access is needed. If a session log overflows the context window,\n  use a DETERMINISTIC pre-retrieval step (chunk/grep the decision-bearing sections; pre-fetch the ticket\n  graph) feeding the single call — never an autonomous agent loop (cheaper, faster, and reproducible, which\n  matters for a gate). (Checking intent against what was actually BUILT would need code tools, but that is a\n  different check — closer to G6/E4 — not intent-vs-plan.)\n- **Don't reinvent.** WS-VISUAL must resist building a canvas editor; prefer an established format + ecosystem\n  (the gate's own \"reinventing-the-wheel\" / \"Frankenstein\" antipatterns, applied to ourselves).\n- **Experiment-artifact hygiene.** Nothing under `docs/experiments/` (the `criteria_v*.json`, the harnesses,\n  the run data) is a durable deliverable — it is reference/grounding only. The durable artifacts are\n  `src/rebar` code, the engine's prompt library, and `docs/`. This epic (and the brainstorm) must not describe\n  any experiment artifact as core/permanent storage.\n- **Agent-vs-single-turn bright line (document this for future maintainers).** A reviewer/criterion is\n  AGENT-tier (a tool-using loop) IF AND ONLY IF reaching its verdict requires probing the LIVE environment —\n  grep/read the repo, run a CLI/API, web-search — i.e. evidence that does NOT already exist in artifacts you\n  can feed it. If all the evidence is in artifacts we already hold (the ticket, its parent/children, linked\n  tickets, a linked session log, the diff under review), FEED them to a single-turn (or 2-STEP) frontier\n  call — that is NOT an agent. Corollaries: (1) \"needs a frontier model + large context\" ≠ \"needs an agent\"\n  (use Opus + feed more context — the mistake originally made for intent-source-fidelity, G3, G4, T10, T11);\n  (2) code-grounding is the SOLE responsibility of E4 / G1G2 / A1 (plus G6 for mechanism-correctness) — NO\n  other criterion independently greps the codebase; it does ticket/plan analysis and DEFERS grounding to\n  them (this is why G4's consumer-impact and T10/T11's existence/convention checks are not their own job);\n  (3) if a source is too large to feed, use a DETERMINISTIC pre-retrieval step, never an autonomous loop.\n  TIEBREAKER: the agent tier is ~85× cost, ~50s, non-deterministic — bad for a gate — so default to\n  single-turn; pay for the loop only when it must probe the environment AND the grounding is not already\n  covered by E4/G1G2/A1. WORKED EXAMPLE (already applied to the experiment registry): G3/G4 (parent-vs-child\n  ticket analysis) and T10/T11 (plan-intrinsic IaC/migration safety) were reclassified AGENT → single-turn;\n  only E4/G1G2/A1/G6/T8/T1/T3 remain agent-tier (they truly probe code / external surfaces / web).\n- **Prompt-engineering guidance for criteria (research-grounded; document + apply).** Persona/role priming\n  is NOT a rigor lever: assigning an expert role or company (\"Principal SWE at Google\", \"Infra Architect at\n  AWS\") does not improve accuracy on objective/evaluation tasks and detailed personas often HURT (Zheng et\n  al. 2024, EMNLP, arXiv 2311.10054 — 162 roles, no gain, random per-question; The Prompt Report, Schulhoff\n  et al. 2024, arXiv 2406.06608 — MMLU 71.6%→66.3% as the persona lengthens; \"Persona is a Double-edged\n  Sword\", arXiv 2408.08631). Roles help tone/style, not correctness, and a \"Principal Engineer\" voice risks\n  confident-but-wrong — the exact failure a gate must avoid. DO NOT add per-criterion role/company personas;\n  the evidence-backed substitute for \"expertise\" is ANCHORING each criterion to a named standard\n  (OWASP/WCAG/Google eng-practices/strong_migrations). The techniques that DO move reliability (use these):\n  atomic yes/no checklists (TICK arXiv 2410.03608, CheckEval arXiv 2403.18771 — already our checklist[] +\n  Pass-2 binary), independent verification (CoVe arXiv 2309.11495, SAFE arXiv 2403.18802 — already Pass-2),\n  calibrated abstention / \"insufficient\" (Cascaded Selective Eval arXiv 2407.18370 — already), REASON-FIRST\n  then structured output (\"Let Me Speak Freely\", Tam et al. 2024, arXiv 2408.02442 — forcing the tool/JSON\n  call first dropped Claude-3-Haiku GSM8K 86.5%→23.4%; FIX APPLIED to the experiment harnesses: a leading\n  `analysis` field on submit_review/emit_findings/verify_finding so the model reasons before the verdict),\n  affirmative anti-FP framing (negation is a weak spot — \"flag only when it would cause rework\", not \"don't\n  nitpick\"), a verbosity-bias guard (\"judge substance, not length\"), and — for production — self-consistency\n  N-sampling + a couple of few-shot calibration exemplars per facet in the prompt library + calibrate each\n  criterion against a small human-graded sample (\"Who Validates the Validators\", arXiv 2404.12272). AVOID\n  cargo-cult emotional prompts (\"take a deep breath\" / \"this is important\") — brittle, model-specific, no\n  robust replication.\n- **2026 update — review-AGENT priming (reinforces the above + adds agent-specific levers).** New work\n  REINFORCES \"personas don't help accuracy\": Hu, Rostami & Thomason 2026 (\"Expert Personas Improve LLM\n  Alignment but Damage Accuracy\", arXiv 2603.18507 — personas help alignment/preference but DROP knowledge\n  accuracy, MMLU 71.6%→66-68%); Luz de Araujo et al. 2025 (\"Principled Personas\", arXiv 2508.19764 — no\n  consistent \"expertise advantage\"). HONEST CAVEAT: no study isolates persona effects inside a multi-step,\n  tool-using REVIEW loop, so the agentic case is genuinely UNTESTED — do not assume agency rescues personas.\n  Agent-review levers that DO have evidence (use instead of identity priming): (1) PLAN-BEFORE-JUDGE — the\n  reviewer produces an evaluation plan, then executes it (EvalPlanner, Saha et al. 2025, arXiv 2501.18099;\n  best-replicated win) — our reason-first `analysis` field is a lightweight form; consider strengthening to\n  \"plan the check, then judge.\" (2) EVIDENCE-ANCHORED locked rubrics beat holistic scoring (Rulers, arXiv\n  2601.08654: QWK 0.73 vs 0.43) — directly validates our locked-rubric + `evidence[]` design. (3) SKEPTIC /\n  \"find only real, evidence-backed defects\" objective; treat reviewer UNANIMITY as a warning, not proof; if\n  ensembling, use DIFFERENT MODEL FAMILIES (Refute-or-Promote, arXiv 2604.19049). (4) TOOL-GROUNDED\n  validation beats model-internal reasoning for low-FP defect review (Verify-Before-You-Fix arXiv 2604.10800;\n  AgenticSCR arXiv 2601.19138) — aligns with E4/G1G2/A1. AVOID multi-agent DEBATE / heavy self-refine: weak,\n  ~3× cost for marginal gain (\"More Rounds, More Noise\", arXiv 2603.16244). (Treat the 2026-preprint numbers\n  as suggestive; the directions match the strongly-replicated 2024 findings.)\n- **Reason-first, precisely (correction).** \"Reason-first\" = do NOT force the structured VERDICT before the\n  model has reasoned (the single-turn force-the-tool-call-immediately case; fixed by the leading `analysis`\n  field). It does NOT mean \"no tool calls first\": an AGENT gathering information via read-only tools BEFORE\n  analysis is correct and expected — info-gathering precedes judgment, and the structured submit comes after.\n  Don't conflate the two.\n- **Anti-false-positive framing must be PINK-ELEPHANT-SAFE (affirmative).** Negation is an LLM weak spot —\n  \"do NOT fabricate / do NOT flag nitpicks / avoid false positives\" makes the prohibited behavior salient.\n  Frame the desired behavior positively: \"report only evidence-grounded findings,\" \"read charitably,\" \"a\n  sound plan correctly yields zero findings.\" (Applied to the SYSTEM / PASS-1 prompts.)\n- **Volume is not quality.** Neither plan length NOR the number of findings measures a good review — when the\n  plan is sound, ZERO findings is the best possible result. State this affirmatively (review quality =\n  accuracy), never as \"don't invent findings\" (pink-elephant).\n- **Charity vs skepticism — reconcile by AXIS and by STAGE (do not let affirmative FP-framing become\n  sycophancy).** \"Read charitably\" must NOT mean \"give the plan's claims the benefit of the doubt\" — that is\n  the sycophancy failure mode the skeptic/critical framing (Refute-or-Promote; the LLM-judge bias literature)\n  exists to counter. Split them: (AXIS) interpret ambiguous LANGUAGE reasonably, but scrutinize SUBSTANCE\n  skeptically — resolve doubt about substance by demanding evidence, not by trusting the plan. (STAGE) in\n  find→verify→decide, false-positive control is the VERIFIER's job, not the finder's: Pass-1 is\n  skeptical-of-the-plan and thorough (a wide, evidence-grounded net), Pass-3 is deterministic, and Pass-2\n  adjudicates TWO competing claims — the plan (\"I'm adequate\") vs the finding (\"defect X\"). Since Pass-1\n  already owns plan-skepticism, Pass-2's skepticism is aimed at the FINDING, implemented AFFIRMATIVELY as\n  \"charitably interpret the plan when judging whether the criticism is justified\": charity-toward-the-plan\n  IS skepticism-of-the-finding — the SAME critical-framing pattern as Pass-1, now pointed at the criticism,\n  and MORE effective because the critical instruction is positive (read the plan charitably) rather than a\n  pink-elephant negative (don't rubber-stamp the finding). The finding stands only if it holds under the\n  plan's most reasonable reading (evidence-ENTAILMENT), judged independently of how confident the plan or the\n  finder sounds. So the whole pipeline is one consistent pattern: skepticism of the claim-under-test at each\n  LLM stage (Pass-1 → the plan; Pass-2 → the finding). Controlling FPs by making the FINDER charitable/timid\n  instead would trade them for sycophantic false NEGATIVES and fight the architecture. (Applied: finder\n  scrutinizes substance; verifier reads the plan charitably to test the finding via entailment.)\n- **Pass-2 verifier shape (model-tiering).** Pass 2 is ONE aggregate verifier call over all findings on a\n  NON-FRONTIER model — the hard generation is Pass-1, Pass-3 is deterministic, so Pass-2 is mechanical\n  binary-answering that a mid-tier model does cheaply. Each finding is judged independently as an unproven\n  claim. (Code-citation findings would need an agentic verifier in the code-review variant; plan-review\n  evidence is mostly plan-text/absence, so one text call suffices and code-grounding stays with E4/G1G2/A1.)\n- **Thin-linear-executor tension.** The engine is deliberately a thin linear executor; review pipelines want\n  fan-out. Resolve whether that is a DSL extension or a scripted-step concern before committing.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- [ ] A canonical `docs/workflow-engine.md` documents intended use + the three-tier LLM-review gating pattern,\n      and the review epics (`5fd2`/`9da1`) point at it.\n- [ ] All LLM functionality (`verify_completion` + the plan-review gate + the existing reviewers) runs on the\n      one workflow-engine substrate, with prompts in the engine's prompt library.\n- [ ] A decision (with rationale) on bidirectional visual editing via an established ecosystem — adopted, or\n      explicitly deferred again WITH the user's sign-off.\n- [ ] A documented capability-vs-alternatives validation (kept-or-pivot).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `docs/workflow-engine.md` exists: intended use, when-to-use-a-workflow, DSL + schema,\n      author/validate/render/run, scripted-vs-agentic steps, prompt-library + eval seam, and the three-tier\n      gating pattern.\n- [ ] `verify_completion` migrated onto the workflow engine (revisiting the `9da1` out-of-scope decision);\n      existing reviewers at parity; the plan-review gate built ON the engine.\n- [ ] The plan-review gate's PRODUCTION prompts/criteria are authored into the engine's prompt-storage +\n      eval seam when the gate is built (`5fd2`). The `criteria_v*.json` experiment artifacts are NOT promoted\n      and NOT moved — they stay under `docs/experiments/`, labeled as reference.\n- [ ] A capability-vs-alternatives review (Langflow / Burr / Temporal / Prefect / Dagster / LangGraph / n8n /\n      Argo) with a kept-or-pivot recommendation.\n- [ ] A bidirectional-visual-editing decision grounded in an established format/ecosystem (not a bespoke\n      canvas), preserving clean git diffs + schema validation.\n- [ ] The workflow-engine DESIGN session log located and built-vs-intent aligned (the deferred visual-editing\n      reconciliation).\n- [ ] A candidate \"intent-source fidelity\" review criterion captured for `5fd2` / `9da1`: a FRONTIER-model\n      (Opus) single-call / 2-STEP criterion that is FED the linked session log + the pre-resolved ticket\n      graph as context (NOT agent/tool-using — text-vs-text comparison, no filesystem access); FIRES ONLY\n      when the ticket is linked to a session log; deterministic pre-retrieval only if a source overflows.\n- [ ] A visual prompt + eval-status review decision (Langfuse / Inspect / promptfoo, or other) — first-class\n      or explicitly out.\n- [ ] `docs/workflow-engine.md` documents the **agent-vs-single-turn bright line** (probe-the-live-environment ⇒ agent; otherwise feed-context single-turn; code-grounding centralized in E4/G1G2/A1) so\n      future maintainers classify new reviewers correctly.\n- [ ] `docs/workflow-engine.md` includes prompt-authoring guidance for reviewer criteria (DO: atomic checklists, independent verify, reason-first-then-structured-output, calibrated abstention, standard-anchoring, affirmative framing, bias controls; DON'T: role/company personas, emotional prompts), with citations.\n- [ ] The reviewer prompt contract enforces REASON-FIRST — a leading reasoning field so reasoning precedes the structured VERDICT (the single-turn force-immediately case); info-gathering tool calls may legitimately precede analysis — carried into the production gate, not just the experiment harness.\n- [ ] Pass-2 verification is specified as a SINGLE aggregate verifier on a NON-FRONTIER model (each finding judged independently); the docs record the model-tiering (Pass-1 capable / Pass-2 non-frontier / Pass-3 deterministic).\n- [ ] Anti-false-positive guidance is authored AFFIRMATIVELY (pink-elephant-safe) and states that zero findings is a valid, often-best result; the docs include the 2026 agent-review levers (plan-before-judge, evidence-anchoring, skeptic objective, tool-grounded validation).\n- [ ] EXISTING (migrated) reviewer prompts (verify_completion / review_ticket / review_code / scan_spec) each have a labeled eval set in the shared eval seam (recall / false-accept / false-fire) drawn from DSO + snap + rebar tickets, so migration is regression-gated — the existing-prompt counterpart to 5fd2's new-prompt eval suite.\n- [ ] The weaker/undeveloped example workflows added to exercise the engine are removed (per Joe's selection), keeping only those that earn their keep; public API / forwarding shims preserved for anything still referenced.\n- [ ] Brainstorm-first: a deep-dive design session precedes implementation; this epic is scope + concerns\n      only until then."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782061273397224001,"uuid":"fc8fd459-a0ab-493c-8457-0de598782702"}